r questions by combining their expertise. What China and India Once Were details how these two cultural giants arrived at their present state, considers their commonalities and divergences, assesses what is at stake in their comparison, and, more widely, questions whether European modernity provides useful contrasts. In jointly composed chapters, contributors explore ecology, polity, gender relations, religion, literature, science and technology, and more, to provide the richest comparative account ever offered of China and India before the modern era. What China and India Once Were establishes innovative frameworks for understanding the historical and cultural roots of East and South Asia in global context, drawing on the variety of Asian pasts to offer new ways of thinking about Asian presents.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh1 aAitken, Molly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenite, Zvi Ben-Dor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBossler, Beverly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrokaw, Cynthia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBusch, Allison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChakrabarty, Dipesh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrossley, Pamela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Richard H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEaton, Richard M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElman, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElman, Benjamin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGuha, Sumit, econtributor.4ctb4